betot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Abbott  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abbott","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>abbod</i>, <i>abbot(t)</i>, <i>abbat</i> ‘abbot’ (Old English <i>abbod</i>) or Old French <i>abet</i> ‘priest’. Both the Old English and the Old French term are derived from Late Latin <i>abbas</i> (genitive <i>abbatis</i>) ‘priest’, from Greek <i>abbas</i>, from Aramaic <i>aba</i> ‘father’. The nickname was presumably a joking reference to a person's behaviour. In the US, the English name is also sometimes a translation of a cognate or equivalent European name, e.g. Italian   Abate  , Spanish   Abad  , or German   Abt  .","History: George Abbot from Yorkshire, England, settled in Andover, MA, in 1640; he had numerous prominent descendants. George Abbott (probably not the same man) died in Rowley, MA, in 1647. Another early migrant was James Abbott, who came from Somerset, England, to Long Island, NY, in the 17th century."]}]},{"name":"Dorothy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."],"variants":[{"name":"Dorothee","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."]},{"name":"Dorothie","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Dorothy de Abbetot was born in 1370, in Badby, Northamptonshire, England. She married Sir Thomas Spencer of Defford about 1391, in Badby, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. She died on 28 November 1416, in England, at the age of 46, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1370–28 November 1416":"1370–28. november 1416","1362–1435":"1362–1435","1384–1433":"1384–1433","1385–1456":"1385–1456","1386–Male":"1386–Surnud","1406–1477":"1406–1477","1408–1477":"1408–1477","1370–1416":"1370–1416","about 1391":"umbes 1391","28 November 1416":"28. november 1416","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","about 1408":"umbes 1408","1435":"1435","1456":"1456","1477":"1477","1433":"1433","1386":"1386","about 1385":"umbes 1385","1408":"1408","1406":"1406","1416":"1416","Colmworth, Bedfordshire, England":"Colmworth, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England",", , , England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1370–28 November 1416":"1370–28. marraskuuta 1416","1362–1435":"1362–1435","1384–1433":"1384–1433","1385–1456":"1385–1456","1386–Male":"1386–Kuollut","1406–1477":"1406–1477","1408–1477":"1408–1477","1370–1416":"1370–1416","about 1391":"noin 1391","28 November 1416":"28. marraskuuta 1416","1385":"1385","1384":"1384","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","